    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tough, compact evergreen shrub with many-branched stems bearing closely-set, needle-like leaves which have the margins rolled under. Flowers white, borne in multiples in rounded, button-like heads and have a fairly-strong honey scent.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9717",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shrubs grow to about 100 cm tall, leaves 5-8 mm long.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9718",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Fynbos endemic found from about Saldanha Bay to Algoa Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9719",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Hardy species found in coastal areas and resistant to drought, wind and fire, so well suited to water-wise coastal gardens. Flowers can be present year-round, but most profuse in late summer and autumn. Pollinated by bees, butterflies and beetles. Plays a significant role in dune stabilization and is harvested and sold as a filler for floral arrangements.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9720",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9721",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flower year-round. Seeds survive for several years in the soil and their germination is stimulated by fire.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9722",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are over 100 regional species in this genus. Of these <i>P. cephalantha</i> is similar in appearance and habits, but has yellow rather than white flowers and occurs only along the west coast. The smaller <i>P. parviflora</i> has a similar range and habits, but only grows to 40 cm tall and has only a few (5-8) woolly florets on each flower head.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9723",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
